The start symbol can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT7 NT20  
2. S → NT33 NT24  

1.  The first token of the string is t6.  
    NT7 can produce only t2, t3, t8, t9, or strings that begin with t4 (via NT7 → NT0 NT30 and NT0 → 't4').  
    Therefore NT7 can never produce a string whose first symbol is t6, so the derivation S → NT7 NT20 is impossible.

2.  For S → NT33 NT24 the first part must be generated by NT33.  
    NT33 can be  

    • a single terminal (t2, t3, t5, t6, t7) or  
    • NT33 → NT9 NT17 (NT17 is a single terminal t0, t2, t5, t9).

    Thus the NT33 portion can be one or more symbols but must end in t0/t2/t5/t9.

    Checking every possible split where the prefix ends in one of those four terminals shows that the remaining suffix would have to be generated by NT24.

    NT24 can expand only as  

    • a single terminal (t0, t2, t3) or  
    • NT24 → NT3 NT32 or  
    • NT24 → NT26 NT6.

    – If NT24 were a single terminal it could not cover the 34-symbol suffix.  

    – If NT24 → NT3 NT32, NT32 must appear at the end; but NT32 can generate only the terminals t0, t3, t5, t6 (through its rules NT32 → 't0' | 't5' | NT32 NT29 and NT29 → 't0' | 't3' | 't6').  
      The given string ends in “… t7 t7 t8 t4 t8”, which contains tokens (t7, t8, t4) that NT32 can never produce, so this expansion is impossible.

    – If NT24 → NT26 NT6, the first symbol produced by NT26 would have to be t0 (the 2nd token of the whole string), which is allowed (NT26 → 't0').  
      NT6 begins with NT16, but NT16 can produce only t2 or something beginning with t0/t3/t5/t6 (via NT16 → NT32 NT1 with NT32 as above).  
      The next actual token is t7, so NT6 cannot start with it, eliminating this expansion.

    Hence no choice for NT33 allows a continuation that NT24 can generate.

Since both possible top-level derivations fail, the string is not in the language.

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT7 NT20  
2. S → NT33 NT24  

Look at the first word of the string (t9).

Case 1: S → NT7 NT20  
• NT7 can either be a single terminal (t2, t3, t8, t9) or the binary form NT0 NT30.  
• If NT7 uses its binary rule, the first token must be the terminal produced by NT0, i.e. t4.  
  The string starts with t9, so this option is impossible.  
• The only remaining possibility is NT7 → t9, consuming the first token.  
  NT20 would then have to generate the remaining 47 tokens beginning with t8.  

NT20’s productions are  
 NT20 → NT23 NT20 | NT12 NT3 | NT3 NT27 | t5 | t6  

To start with t8, the only feasible production is NT20 → NT3 NT27 with NT3 → t8.  
That forces NT27 to produce the next token in the string (t0).  
But NT27’s first symbol is always NT14 (from NT27 → NT14 NT24 / NT14 NT11), and NT14 can only yield t9 or t5.  
Hence NT27 can never start with t0, making this entire branch impossible.

Case 2: S → NT33 NT24  
NT33 can begin with a single terminal {t5, t2, t3, t6, t7} or with NT9/NT19 in its binary rules; none of these can produce an initial t9.  
Thus this expansion also cannot match the string.

Since both possibilities for S fail at the very first token, the grammar cannot derive the given string.
